\subsection{Macrophage cells}
When active macrophages meet viral particles, there is an increase in these cells at inflammation sites during early infection stages, and a small proportion suffer from infection. The mathematical simulations showed that 34 \% of total active macrophages become infected (almost two-fold the value found in [29] during the installation phase of HIV pathogenesis), and this level reaches 43 \% during the asymptomatic phase. The kinetics of macrophage proliferation show a pseudo-steady state in infected macrophage dynamics (Fig.~\ref{fig4}), reaching an average content of 18 cells $\mu l^{-1}$. Considering that nearly one-third of active macrophages become infected, its importance as a viral proliferation reservoir and infection maintenance is significant.\\
